Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California, Santa Cruz studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneity in stellar clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow to look among the stars related, that is, originated from a single cluster.
The results of their research were published in the journal Nature, and briefly available on the university's website.
The reason for the same chemical composition of the nearby stars is the turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas, preceding the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of star-relatives.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster can lead to differences in its chemical content from that in relatives in the cluster.
The results of the simulations conducted by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, the experts simulated two streams of interstellar gas using a supercomputer, which together formed a cloud.
This object for several million years under the influence of its own gravity is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
Scientists added paint tags to the original gas streams and found that rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud achieves a high degree of chemical homogeneity.
According to astrophysicists, their research proves that it is possible to look for stars-relatives by chemical composition, as well as to determine possible regions of formation of such objects.
