Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill that would protect union organizing as a civil right.
"Where there are unions, there are middle-class jobs," said Ellison, a Democrat from Minnesota who is co-chair of the Progressive Caucus Congress.
That's why I'm proud to present the Workers' Rights Act, along with the civil rights symbol John Lewis.
This groundbreaking bill will give workers the same legal opportunity to discriminate against union organizations as in other forms of discrimination, stopping opponents of trade unions
Changing the Labour Regulation Act to allow workers facing discrimination for participating in unionization to seek justice in civil courts - and receive damages and punitive payments - is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
But this is certainly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the co-sponsors of the bill are proposing is to remember a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that unions have suffered in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country - Americans once supported countries around the world in accepting, expanding and respecting labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that hideki Tojo's paramilitary autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions played a role in the formation of the new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that "the right of workers to organize, negotiate, and collective action is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers will need to be organized and heard in a new state, the Germans included an article that openly read: "The right to form associations to protect and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or field of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe on this right will not be legally binding; measures aimed at these purposes will be considered illegal.
When former first lady Eleanor Roosevelt was chairwoman of the International Human Rights Commission, which drafted the World Declaration on Human Rights, which in 1948 would be adopted by the United Nations as a world agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to protect their interests."
For generations, Americans have taken for granted the basic position that labour rights are human rights.
When that country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions - and for the union to participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies - should be protected.
At a time when these rights are being attacked in America, it is wise, indeed, to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased them.
By raising the standard of living of millions, trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised an entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers, as it should be, and to us.
Official recognition of labour rights as a human right - and increased protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination against union organization - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are reviving the ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
Judge temporarily blocks law that could close all abortion clinics in Louisiana
In the United States, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the enactment of a Louisiana law that his supporters say would likely close all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under the measure, which was signed into law by Louisiana Gov. Bobby Jinadle in June and was supposed to take effect on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have the authority to admit patients to a hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge's decision means that for the time being doctors can continue to perform legal abortions while continuing to seek such powers.
"Plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally while continuing to obtain authority," Justice John deGrevells wrote in his decision.
A hearing will be scheduled within a month, at which the judge will make a more permanent decision on the law.
Abortion rights advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a string of rulings against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to get hospital powers.
"Today's decision ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from a treacherous law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights," said Nancy Northup, president and chief executive of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which filed a lawsuit to stop the law on behalf of three of the state's five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from two clinics who did not act as plaintiffs in the case and also applied for admission authority.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed similar laws, and courts recently declared such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of a Texas law that would have shut down most of the remaining clinics in that state were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion rights advocates, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say admission laws impose restrictions on physicians that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion object that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some have also noted their positive effects in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has the authority to take care of a hospital, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing the procedure, the doctor would stop performing the procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not penalize abortion doctors while their applications for admission are pending.
What will lead to the introduction of quotas for domestic products
At least half of the products for each type of goods in the range of retail chains should be Russian-made, said Oleg Nilov, a member of the State Duma from the "Just Russia" faction.
The parliamentarian has prepared a bill aimed at introducing protective measures against domestic producers, Izvestia newspaper reports.
The document will still be detailed to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
This applies to goods that are not manufactured in Russia. <...> For the rest of the groups of products that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic manufacturers," Nilov told the publication.
Together with amendments to the article "On the basics of state regulation of trade activities in Russia" the bill provides for amendments to the Tax Code, setting a reduced VAT rate of 10% when selling products produced in Russia.
The idea to introduce a 50% quota in retail chains is part of the incentive package for Russian manufacturers.
On the shelves will appear several times more domestic goods.
However, the initiative can have both a positive and a negative effect, experts say.
According to Sergei Litvinenko, a lawyer for Taxovik, a member of the independent expert center "Public Duma" for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industries, the effect will be positive, and will lead to growth.
In the plus will be farmers, farmers, small shops.
They will be able to sell more, which means that the profit will grow.
In addition, they will have the right to dictate to retailers their terms and prices, because they will be forced to buy their goods.
Russian manufacturers will be able to increase their activities and sales, which will lead to the payment of higher taxes than before.
This will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will start to expand, some are faster to develop, will contribute to GDP growth.
Russia's dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, however, not immediately," the expert notes.
Previously, Russian enterprises often could not break into the shelves of local stores because of the high competition from foreign counterparts.
Now, after the embargo, this niche has been liberated and it is possible to breathe a sigh of relief.
But we should not forget that after all the necessary approvals and sanitary checks on the Russian market will receive food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia.
In other words, now is the "moment of calm" when the former players have already left, and the new ones have not yet arrived.
After almost a month we can talk about the increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as the increase in prices for finished products," Tamara Kasyanova, first vice-president of the Russian public organization "Russian Club of Financial Directors", told AIF.ru.
Definitely, the idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will allow to consolidate the sector for local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, and not with goods, which are cheaper due to subsidies from another state.
In other words, the struggle for the buyer will unfold between companies operating under the same laws of the industry.
On the other hand, Kasyanova notes, Russian manufacturers are able to meet 50% of the internal needs of compatriots not on all counts.
And in this situation, the retail chains will have to "reach" the share of Russian goods to half of the range.
In this regard, there are growing fears that the shelves will receive substandard goods.
It is possible that foreign products with broken labels will be supplied under the guise of produced in Russia," the expert adds.
Large trade networks, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers, will feel the negative effect of the introduction of quotas.
It is logical that foreign suppliers themselves will suffer in this situation, as the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not rule out that the law on quotas on domestic goods can affect consumers as well.
The fact is that some products of Russian production can yield on the quality of imported counterparts, while stores will be able to inflate prices for the second, as a scarce commodity.
Economists started talking about the idea of import substitution forgotten in the early 2000s in February of this year because of the continuous devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the background of difficult relations with the West, the issue of abandoning imported products is becoming even more urgent.
The law is intended to oblige retailers to take into account domestic manufacturers when forming orders.
Then we will take the path of import substitution much faster and more confidently, and the system of planning production for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time frame," said MP Oleg Nilov.
A quota mechanism would be particularly effective for those agricultural sectors where the potential was particularly high, for example in the dairy industry, where imports accounted for 25 per cent.
Our farmers are really able to completely cover the shelves of Russian shops.
In addition, meat production can get a strong boost.
As you know, the largest share of imports is saved by beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% is still accounted for by Russian products," Kasyanova said.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will contribute to import substitution and can speed up the process.
However, this initiative will not lead to import substitution by itself, as it requires a set of measures, Litvinenko believes.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be brought from abroad, which means that there will be no full-fledged import substitution, but significant steps in this direction will be made.
In addition, it is not enough to set quotas, it is necessary to establish the production of domestic products in the country in order to meet these quotas.
These quotas will provide such guarantees," the expert says.
Untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James posted a video of their late mother's memory, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who work in rural Australia face a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those living in cities.
Researchers analysed disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that just 35 per cent had lived five years after being diagnosed.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the Institute of Medical Research of the iMR Berghofer reported that those who live in regions and remote areas of the state are 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those who live in urban areas.
READ MORE: New drugs may slow lung cancer and ovarian cancer
Researchers traced the women's medical pathway for seven years.
Dr Jordan said the woman's age at the time of diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socioeconomic status also affected the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those with cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state, the probability of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those who lived in urban areas.
While the study was not intended to determine why women living outside cities were more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr Jordan suggested that late diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment were possible factors.
"This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly found in big cities," she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing the number of out-of-home services that would allow professionals to treat women closer to home, and support programs for people undergoing treatment far from their home, could help.
Dr Jordan said that regardless of geographic location, the study found that long life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, highlighting the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young Gold Coast mother, Elisha Neave, was told she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
