Inflation came out of vacation.
Will Russians feel a sharp rise in prices
As a result of cross-sanctions of Russia and the West, inflation in Russia will accelerate and will not meet the forecasts of the authorities, analysts of VTB Capital are convinced.
According to experts, the postponed consequences of anti-sanctions will lead to an inflation shock in the first quarter of 2015, RBC Daily writes.
According to the latest forecast of the Ministry of Economic Development, in 2014 inflation will be 6.5-7.5%, next year and even less - 6.5%.
However, according to Kommersant newspaper, this week the IER should make "small but principled" adjustments to the macroeconomic forecast until 2017.
According to the newspaper, the agency can lower the estimate of inflation for 2015, which will eliminate the expected zeroing of income growth of the population.
The forecast assumed that the food sanctions of the Russian Federation are valid for a year - until August 2015.
How could such a high inflation be assumed in such a situation?
The current situation assumes a one-time shock, but the downward trend of inflation will not change," said the source of the newspaper in the Ministry of Finance.
Economists from VTB Capital do not share the expectations of the financial and economic bloc of the government regarding inflation and forecast price growth in 2014 at the level of 8%.
The main effect of food bans will come together with the possible introduction of a sales tax (NSP) in the regions of Russia in 2015, experts are convinced.
Inflation peak of 9% will be in February, after which the annual rate of price growth will decline, experts believe.
By the way, last week Rosstat summed up the first inflationary results after Russia imposed "careful sanctions."
AIF.ru interviewed experts and found out their inflation expectations.
Artem Deev, head of the analytical department of AForex FC:
Price growth is already observed in the main segments of goods.
Moreover, when socially important products began to become more expensive, the Government was forced to launch measures of systemic monitoring of price stability in order to prevent the risks of unreasonable price increases in the short term.
Suppliers and retailers are already reporting on a daily basis to regulators to let the authorities know exactly who, when and for what reason initiates price increases.
The main factors in the growth of the consumer price index continue to be the enormous rate of capital outflows, excessive refinancing of the banking sector by the Russian megaregulator, internal conversion due to the flight of the population into foreign currency, as well as an embargo on the import of food products from countries that have joined the sanctions against Russia.
If inflationary pressures remained under control, the value of a basket of minimum products would not have jumped by 12% in a quarter alone.
The ban on the import of food products provoked a shock of supply in the domestic market and led to a perfectly logical increase in the final cost.
Since at the current stage we are not able to fully launch the import substitution mechanism, as well as to increase the self-sufficiency of the Russian market through domestic production, retaliatory sanctions will continue to carry risks of growth of the inflation component.
If we add here also the fiscal reasons associated with the lack of confidence in the national currency, as well as the worsened prospects for economic growth, by the end of this year inflation may well exceed 8%.
Alexander Razuvayev, Director of Alpari's Analytical Department
In the 1990s, inflation sometimes reached 20-30% per month, in zero it was also above the current level, another thing that then it was compensated by rapid economic growth.
I think at the end of the year inflation will be 8-8.5%.
Plato Maguta, Asset Manager, Maguta Foundation
The external factor associated with sanctions against Russia is still successfully restrained, but if there is a further increase in pressure, first of all, on the financial sector - it can lead to some difficulties and increase inflation expectations of the population, which are usually traditionally manifested in purchases of cash in order to secure their savings.
It can be assumed that the government, the Central Bank of the Russian Federation and the Ministry of Finance will try to soften the smooth weakening of the ruble, both by market methods and by state regulation.
But price growth begins traditionally after the summer lull and may become more tangible this autumn.
The target level of consumer inflation in Russia of 7.5% is likely to stand, as Russia has more financial savings.
Gardening centres are saddened by the decline in the number of homeowners
The fall, driven by an exceptional reduction in the number of homeowners under the age of 35, could lead to gardening centres losing tens of millions of pounds a year when today's young consumers reach the "basic age of gardening," according to an HTA study reported by the Financial Times.
According to the report, people renting spend on average 55 per cent of the amount that owners of their own homes spend on gardening.
It mentions the increase in the number of people living in highly urbanized areas without gardens, the popularity of paving yards in front of the house for parking and the reduction of garden sizes as other threats to the industry, whose annual sales are estimated to be 5 billion.
In Greater London, where the number of homeowners has fallen from 61 per cent to 43 per cent in six years, the UK has the lowest level of spending on household goods.
The HTA and the Royal Horticultural Society reported that renting and lack of space for a garden does not mean that people cannot grow plants.
Guy Barter, chief horticulture adviser at rhS, said: "Growing plants in containers, for example, is particularly popular with tenants who can carry plants with them when they move."
The HTA report defined the period between 1997 and 2005 as the "golden age" of gardening retailing as a result of the increase in the number of homeowners and economic prosperity from the late 1980s to the mid-1990s.
It also predicts that the market will improve this year thanks to better weather after unfavourable conditions in March and April last year.
