China's largest companies unite against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China's largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and Internet giants Tencent Holdings (social media, messenger, etc.) and Baidu (the largest Chinese search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online trading market with Alibaba.
However, catching up with the miracle of the Chinese Internet, which left behind even its American rivals - eBay and Amazon.com, will not be easy.
The Union's largest
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($814 million) in the joint venture, 70% of it will be owned by Wanda and 15% each of the Internet companies, Wanda Group said in a statement.
The company is scheduled to be registered in Hong Kong.
The JV will combine Baidu's search services with the popular social platform WeChat (the largest social network in China with a total of about 438 million users), Tencent and Wanda Infrastructure.
In addition to a network of 40 luxury hotels, Wanda Group operates at least 49 commercial properties across China and 40 shopping malls.
Last year, the company invested 50 billion yuan (more than $8 billion) in the construction of a film studio and theme park in Tsingtao (a city in eastern China on the shores of the Yellow Sea).
The project is expected to attract more than 1 million visitors annually and generate a profit of $960 million.
In addition, Wanda owns the American cinema chain AMC Entertainment Holdings, which makes the company the largest cinema operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all its shopping malls, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, which will be developed by the newly created competitor Alibaba.
According to Dong Tse, who will lead the new company, thanks to the merger, Wanda will be able to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million people to 100 million by next year.
The new site should become the world's largest online-to-offline platform, Dong Tse notes.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract customers online so that they come to regular offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O is coupon services like Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
"O2O is the largest "pie" in online commerce," said Wanda CEO Wang Jianlin (quoted by Bloomberg).
"Right now, there is no real O2O site in China, and in this situation the chances are approximately equal to that of everyone," he said.
The Chinese online trading market is the largest in the world, and According to McKinsey's estimates, its volume will more than triple by 2015 compared to 2011, to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has grown to 632 million, Bloomberg quotes official statistics: it is more than the population of any country in the world, except India.
And it is predicted that by 2015 this number could grow to 850 million people.
The Union of the Richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huaten was until recently China's richest man, but according to Bloomberg's Millionaires Index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already overtaken him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma's fortune is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion comes from his stake in Alibaba.
Baidu's chief executive Robin Li is now third among China's richest men, while Wanda's Wang Jianlin is fourth in the rankings.
"It's very interesting to see this battle: the three richest people are joining forces to challenge the even richer," Cao Lei, director of the China E-Commerce Research Center in Hangzhou, told Bloomberg.
But he believes the new company is unlikely to be able to seriously compete with Alibaba immediately after its creation: "Rome cannot be built in one day."
The fact that it is not so easy to compete with Alibaba not only new companies, but also honored leaders of the world Internet trade, is evidenced by the report published the day before on the financial performance of Alibaba for the last quarter.
Alibaba is often described as a cross between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June the Chinese company earned more than both of its U.S. rivals combined.
Alibaba's net profit for the period is almost double that of its competitors - it nearly tripled year-on-year to $1.99 billion.
"Alibaba still has huge potential to generate money, thanks in large part to its mobile applications," an analyst at Hong Kong's Arete Research Service told Bloomberg.
According to the updated Alibaba prospectus on the website of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the number of active mobile users of the company's services in July amounted to 188 million, which is significantly higher than the March figure (163 million people).
At the same time, 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions in the past quarter were on mobile devices.
Alibaba will name the value of its shares before the IPO.
According to an average estimate of 11 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $187 billion after the share sale.
According to Bloomberg sources, Alibaba's debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) may take place as early as September 16.
The company's road show, preceded by this event, will start on September 3.
Alibaba's IPO is expected to be the highest in NYSE history and will allow the company to raise about $20 billion.
So far, the record for the amount of funds raised on the U.S. exchanges belonged to the payment system Visa, which in 2008 held an initial public offering of its shares, earning $17.9 billion.
