The calculation of the estimates of construction sites in Russia will take place in a new way
The Federal Antitrust Service takes special control over pricing, regulation of the construction industry, as well as problems of connection to networks.
The FAS has established an expert council to develop competition in the construction sector.
At his meeting, Vadim Solovyov, head of the FAS's housing, construction and natural resources control department, said that "today's calculation of the estimates of construction sites is completely incomprehensible."
Regulatory framework makes pricing opaque and can lead to unreasonable construction price, according to the FAS.
And they propose the cost of construction of state property facilities at the design stage to determine on the basis of market prices constructive solutions instead of the current estimates and single prices for technological operations.
These proposals have been put on the road map and are currently under consideration in the Ministry of Construction.
"Replacing the traditional estimated documentation in construction with the calculations of structural elements should lead to less corruption in the industry," Vadim Solovyov explained to RGB.
After all, now the estimate counts every bolt and nut, and it is not always possible to check everything, so sometimes in the documentation unscrupulous construction companies can bury "whole tractors."
The Ministry agrees with the FAS.
"The first developments on the transition to the calculation of the cost by structural elements are already there: methods have been developed to calculate prices for constructive solutions, to draw up estimates on these indicators," the head of the department of urban planning and architecture of the Ministry of Construction Elena Shchukova told RGB.
Road construction has been selected as a pilot.
However, experts believe that the problem is much more serious.
Anatoly Demjanko, head of the profi-invest construction company, told RGB that the estimates are out of date, but no other mechanism has been proposed for business.
"As for the proposed calculations on structural elements, in practice it is difficult to implement, as the construction of buildings often uses completely different technologies," he said.
It is no secret that the construction market is developing largely due to the state order.
According to Ekaterina Lezina, chairman of the board of the Expert Community of State Order Professionals, the state is now the most solvent customer.
Vladimir Malakhov, deputy director of engineering at Rosatom's industrial capital construction center, drew attention to the fact that today the market is conditionally divided into companies that have access to the portfolio of contracts, and companies that have monopoly competencies and do not allow competitors to enter the field.
He believes that the creation of a transparent market is possible only if access to contracts is protected from someone's management influence as much as possible.
At the expert council it was proposed to form a system of state order in such a way that the same executor is not entitled to receive more than one contract worth more than 1 billion rubles or several contracts worth more than 1 billion rubles.
The Ministry believes that this approach should be evaluated in terms of the impact on business, as well as the efficiency of construction management.
As explained by Elena Shchukova, in this case it will be necessary to give the customer the functions of a general contractor, which will lead to an increase in the staffing of the customer and budgetary expenses for its maintenance.
At the same time, the customer's specialists will have to have the knowledge to assess the quality of the work performed by contractors, as well as their safety.
Often, this breakdown will require determining who will be responsible for the security of the object as a whole.
In addition, this approach may lead to an outflow of highly qualified public procurement participants due to the lack of interest in obtaining a government order for incomplete work and a small amount of contract.
Alexander Evstashenkov, deputy head of the expert advisory center of the Institute of Procurement, believes that now the procedure of the state order has turned into a business game for the care of the contractor.
And he gave this example: "a participant should specify "specific indicators" without specifying the words "or equivalent" when filling out an application, "should be," "from," "more," "less," "similar," "or," "type," "similar type," "no lower," "below," "may," "may have," "maybe," "earlier," "no earlier," "no higher," "not allowed, etc.
Customers often abuse their right to set requirements for the content of an application submitted by contractors.
Another problem 44-Fz, according to Evstashenkov, was the need to assess the quality of work through the "paper" proposal of the participant at the application stage.
Considering the application of the participant, it is really possible to evaluate only the qualification of the contractor, but not the quality of work, which has not even started, - the expert believes.
The quality of the work can be assessed only when they are accepted.
The expert council also proposed to move the marginal income from the upper to the lower echelon, so that the intermediate contractors would disappear.
Chairman of the expert council, State Secretary, deputy head of FAS Andrei Tsarikovskiy believes that this should not be done, as the general contractor should be responsible for the order.
Otherwise it will turn out, as in Arkady Raikin's famous reprise "Atelier": "Is there a claim to the buttons?".
Israeli children return to school after Gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children in areas near the Gaza Strip went back to school on Monday after spending the summer in bomb shelters when rockets and mines rained down on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed as the territory recovered from the fighting.
The start of school hours brought a sense of joy and excitement to the missile-affected settlements of southern Israel, but the traces of the fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, staff at the Pashosh kindergarten, which was hit by a rocket, removed traces of shrapnel from walls and children's slides before the students came.
"We're a little scared, but we're excited about the future," said Ronit Barth, a Kibbutz Saad resident and English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really need to return to a measured life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Barth, said it was "a little weird" to start going back to school.
"It was a difficult time and we didn't leave their homes at all," she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited the kibbutz, which is located near the Border with Gaza, to express his support.
Before the cease-fire stopped the war last week, thousands of border residents such as Saad did not go outside or fled their homes to safer areas further from the Gaza Strip to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the Gaza border where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a Palestinian mine, doubt that they should go back.
The Department for Education said about a dozen families had not yet returned.
Their children were sent to other schools at this time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a town on the border with Gaza that has been hit hard by Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study diligently and said, "We will do everything we can to give you knowledge and ensure your safety."
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite truce last Tuesday.
The cease-fire immediately put an end to the fighting, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas' demand to lift the Egypt-Israel blockade of Gaza and the opening of airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its arms and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers who died in the war.
A new phase of indirect talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
More than 2,100 Palestinians have been killed in the war, three-quarters of whom were civilians and at least 494 children, according to estimates by the Palestinian side and the UN.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; despite this, it has not provided substantial evidence to support this allegation.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians, including one Thai worker, were killed.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza militants fired 4,591 rockets and mines at Israeli cities, mostly in the south of the country.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, has carried out more than 5,000 airstrikes and other attacks.
Israeli attacks have damaged and destroyed thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip, and an estimated 250,000 people have taken refuge in more than 100 schools that have been converted into shelters.
With tens of thousands of people still in shelters and fighting continuing, education officials postponed the start of the school year last week.
"I hope that the school will soon open so that we can complete our education as children around the world and Jewish children," said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in a Gaza school.
