Genetic disorder is often misdiagnosed
A British woman reported that she had spent many years thinking she was going to die after a misdiagnosis.
Karyn Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking she had only a few years left to live after she was diagnosed with another condition.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Tuta disease (CMT) - a group of hereditary disorders that cause nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK said the misdiagnosis was a common problem among people with CMET because so little was known about the condition.
Some 23,000 people in the UK are thought to have CMT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, insecure gait and clenched toes.
Patients may feel numb or pain, and the condition is not cured and progresses, which means that symptoms increase over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich's Ataxia (AF) - a condition for which the prognosis was very bad.
Rogers thought she would be confined to a wheelchair by the time she was 18 and would die before she turned 30.
The mother-of-two, now 51, said: 'As a child I knew I couldn't do what others did.
I fell every day, and it took me more time.
I could never ride a roller or skateboard with other kids, and I was bullied a lot at school because of the way I walked and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release her Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked into the medical card when her doctor left the room and it was written that she had AF.
"I felt guilty because I stuck my nose where I shouldn't, so I didn't tell anyone, but I went home, found information about the condition in the library and wrote to the AF Association," she said.
When I received the information in response, I was shocked and experienced the most terrible panic possible.
I thought I'd be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I was 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in that span.
I went through this alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she turned 17, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she thought and asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up, hugged me and said, "My darling, I don't think you have this disease because you'd already be in a wheelchair."
I think you have something that poses a much less life-threatening way.
After several genetic examinations, she was found to have AMM.
"When he explained what CMIT was, I thought I had pulled out a lucky ticket," she said.
The charity CMIT UK has announced a month of information about CHT to try to draw attention to the disease.
Tax burden on Washington zone entrepreneurs grows as economy recovers
A rebounding economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country increased moderately last year as the economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study released last week, and companies in the Washington area are no exception.
Companies in the District, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $27.6 billion to the state's coffers and locally in fiscal 2013, a 3.8 percent increase from the $26.6 billion raised in 2012.
The tax burden on business by state and local level increased by 4.3 percent last year, to $671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after years of declines in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes rose faster, 4.3 percent, than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by the professional services firm, Ernst and Young, and the Center for State Taxation, a tax policy group.
More than half of the district's tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from business taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland's tax revenue comes from firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, brings the lowest amount of tax revenue, proportionately, from entrepreneurs.
Much of the increase in tax revenue is driven by a return to the value of real estate companies, the researchers said, which has raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three consecutive years of growth of less than 1 percent.
While large states such as California, New York and Texas account for a large share of these revenues, the same seems to be happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the District, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012 - an increase of 4.2 percent from the previous year.
But the observed return on property values has no similar effect on the growth of tax revenue across the state and locally in Maryland, where property taxes barely exceed one-fifth of company tax bills.
Companies in Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of state and local tax bills in the form of real estate taxes.
"What's happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, is owned by either the government or a nonprofit that doesn't pay property taxes," said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the State Tax Center.
Thus, Maryland has to rely much more, for example, on income taxes to pay for the same services that exist in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
The income of entrepreneurs also seems to be on the mend, according to these data.
Companies in the region declared $2.3 billion in state income tax, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland has collected $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the most in the region.
Although trends are directed in the same direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at the local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three localities.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the national average of 4.3 percent, while growth in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 percent.
In Virginia alone, there has been a lower-than-average rise in tax revenues, or 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of the three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate) of 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the district it is relatively high - 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower taxes for entrepreneurs across the state and locally and, in general, a more favorable climate for business taxes than Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its neighbor from the south.
North Carolina recently signed legislation reducing the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, the same as in Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet tax revenue targets next year, the law could bring the income tax rate for entrepreneurs to even 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington area seem to be feeling better and thus paying more taxes across the state and locally, according to a recent study.
Taxes for entrepreneurs paid in the form of individual income tax by small business owners - the transitional structure under which most small firms are arranged - in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia rose 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, with a much faster rate of growth than taxes for entrepreneurs as a whole.
Researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenue across the country is likely to continue this year, with state and local tax receipts up 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington area may lag behind, as the decline in federal spending affects the labor market in the region.
