MPs proposed to speed up the entry into force of the law on personal data
If the initiative is successful, the data of Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015
The State Duma has introduced a draft law providing for the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is based on the legislative activities of the lower house.
It was sponsored by State Duma deputies Vadim Moneyn, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Yevgeny Fedorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parakhin ("Fair Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (COMMUNISTF).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to more prompt and effective enforcement of the rights of Russian citizens to the safety of personal data and compliance with the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunications networks.
The law, which is in a hurry for parliamentarians, obliges to keep personal data of Russians processed through the Internet in the territory of the Russian Federation.
It also makes it mandatory to record, organize, store, store, refine and extract personal data of Russian citizens, in databases located in Russia, as well as specifying the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right on the basis of a court decision to restrict access to information processed in violation of Russian law in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called "black lists" of offending sites - an automated information system "Register of violators of the rights of subjects of personal data."
This law was adopted by the State Duma in the summer.
The bill was sponsored by Andrei Lugovoi and Vadim Moneyn from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the Communist Party.
Moneyn and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill on the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in Russia will have to pay rent
Commenting on the bill introduced today in the State Duma, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy Leonid Levin said that he sees no problems for the postponement of the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own repositories of personal data of Russians in the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "from Rostelecom, which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent and already provide their servers, from Mail Group, from Western companies that now provide their servers."
"In addition, there are several independent data centers ready to cooperate in this area," he added.
"If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work in the Russian Federation, I see no problem - they will get technological opportunities for accommodation," Levin concluded.
Controversial bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Electronic Communications Association expressed concern that if the bill was passed, Russians would no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about online booking services for flights and hotels.
According to the association, "the bill deprives the subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation the right to dispose of their own data imperatively determining that their record, systemization, etc. should be provided only in databases located in the territory of the Russian Federation."
The RAEC statement stresses that a more effective measure would be to establish a mechanism to inform the user about where the recording is carried out, to organize his personal data.
In this case, he will be able to choose on what territory these actions will be carried out.
The adoption of such bills on the "localization" of personal data in other countries has led to the withdrawal of global services and to significant economic losses.
