"Europrotocol" instead of the help of the traffic police
Payments on the casco can be received without the help of the traffic police - so the Central Bank intends to stimulate the introduction of the "europrotocol" in Russia.
The Bank of Russia has developed a draft directive according to which from September 1 this year to receive payments for the casco insured motorist will be able to do without a certificate of traffic police.
However, we are talking only about cases where the accident was registered under the "europrotocol" without the participation of the traffic police.
That is, if only two cars were involved in the accident, there are no physically injured persons, the damage does not exceed the set limit and both drivers have reached an agreement in the question of who is responsible for the accident.
From August 2, the limit of payments under the "europrotocol" is 50 thousand rubles, and from October 1 in Moscow, St. Petersburg, as well as in the Moscow and Leningrad regions it will be raised to 400,000 rubles.
The bottom line is that often even with minor injuries, in a situation where an accident can be issued by "europrotocol", drivers who got into an accident, call DPS.
After all, if there was a policy, it was impossible to get a refund on it without a certificate of traffic police.
The parameters outlined in the draft guidance are designed to remove this obstacle to the introduction of the "euro protocol" in Russia.
According to them, the maximum payment for a cascading in connection with an accident, issued without traffic police officers, should not be lower than the limit on the "europrotocol".
But at the same time it can not be higher than the limit defined in the insurance contract of the casco.
The idea is certainly useful and theoretically able to unload both DPS and road employees.
But, most likely, it will not delight neither motorists nor insurers.
The latter are already talking about the serious threat of the growth of fraud, which can lead to the introduction of new rules of payments on cascading.
