The Ministry of Finance wants to ban the bearer's savings certificates, but will allow banks to make them an analogue of irrevocable deposit.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will ban the bearer's savings certificates.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, as the rates here are higher than on bank deposits.
The fact is that the bearer's savings certificates do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper for the bank, as there is no need to make deductions to the Deposit Insurance Agency (DEPOSIT Insurance Agency) fund.
The piquancy of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken because of small and medium-sized banks distributing such certificates, and Sberbank and Bank of Moscow, which, according to the ACB, control 98% of the profile market, will suffer from it.
And the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to the agency's calculations, is about 3.5%.
The problem, the ACB explains, is that customers of a small bank who bought such a certificate, in case of revocation of his license, try to get money in the ACB.
Some savers, not having sufficient financial literacy and buying savings certificates for the bearer, can assume that their investments are insured.
The justified absence of insurance payments on these certificates in the event of the revocation of the bank's license can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the practice of the agency, there were cases when holders of certificates tried to recover insurance compensation through the court," the AWU said.
The problem, of course, is far-fetched.
After all, no one will pay buyers certificates anyway, because they do not have the right to compensation from the state by law.
If it were that the instrument is not insured in the ACB, with it would be banned and metal accounts, which citizens' funds are counted in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but their existence is not yet attempted.
The fact is, most likely, that bearer certificates are a very convenient security, which can actually act as a quasi-money.
At the same time, their movement is almost beyond control: any client of the bank can buy a certificate, transfer to any citizen, and before cashing such a certificate can change many owners.
It is no coincidence that the bill stipulates that the savings certificate must be a necessary security, which should be stored in the depository.
And to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to be issued without the right of early repayment.
That is, an analogue of irrevocable contribution, which bankers have long dreamed of, is introduced.
