Forensic examination showed that the cause of the crash was the increased speed of landing, the failure of the crew to comply with standard procedures on landing, as well as the unintentional release of engines to the increased speeds of direct thrust.
The Red Wings Tu-204 aircraft, en route from Prague to Moscow, crashed on December 29, 2012 while landing at Moscow's Vnukovo airport.
The aircraft rolled out of the runway and caught fire.
The aircraft commander, co-pilot and flight engineer died at the scene.
Two flight attendants were taken to hospitals, where they later died from their injuries.
Three other flight attendants, hospitalized with serious injuries, were treated for long periods of time.
In addition, the driver of the car, who was driving on the Kiev highway at the time of the crash, was seriously injured.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
The transport prosecutor's office conducted an inspection at Red Wings after the crash, which revealed numerous violations.
In February 2013, the airline's license was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
