Anger turned out to be the most universal and functional emotion of man
Angry facial expression is biologically universal for humanity, and every organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not accidental, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists in Australia and the Us have found.
They described their discoveries in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and can be read briefly about them in a press release from the University of California, Santa Barbara.
Angry facial expressions - shifted and lowered eyebrows, outstretched in a thin line of lips, bloated nostrils - are the same in all cultures, and make it even blind from birth to children who have never seen it, notes the study's lead author Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists have found that this emotion has emerged to effectively dispute during conflict.
The more physical damage one person can inflict on another, the more opportunities he has to dictate his terms, and he brings it to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
Researchers have found evidence of another hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to get angry and move to hand-wringing, consider themselves entitled to impose conditions unfavorable to them, and prefer forceful methods of conflict resolution peacefully.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily an "emotion of bargaining", the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups, creating an angry expression, should present the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thus force as soon as possible to accept its conditions to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers simulated on a computer the faces where each of the seven elements of the angry face was present or missing, and showed them to informants.
Although the lowered eyebrows or forward chin separately did not make the face angry, the participants of the study recognized the stronger physical participants with such traits.
Human anger, like that of animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one's own power, forcing to accept and obey.
A man inflates his nostrils and presses his lips for the same purpose as a frog that inflates, or a baboon that shows off its fangs.
"Anger is "started" by the refusal of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form, as effectively as possible demonstrating to the opposite side of the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of an angry face is arbitrary, they all express the same thing," said anthropologist John Tooby.
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles to the TV and radio company "Crimea"
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget in 2014 to the autonomous non-profit organization "Crimea" TV and Radio Company.
This is stated in a draft government resolution prepared by the agency, which was read by Lenta.ru.
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed "to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of the modern information space in the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the purchase of equipment."
In particular, the allocated money is supposed to convert the hardware-studio unit, video walls, central hardware and video silver.
It is also planned to purchase a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter.
In addition, the company will pay for the use of the fiber optic communication line (VOLS) and repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the federal budget provided for the Ministry of Communications.
The state broadcaster Crimea was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the coverage of the television signal of the tv and radio company makes up more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, "Crimea" TV and Radio Company received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.